acticed as a country physician in Piermont, New Hampshire, where four of his seven children with Emeline died before the age of three. The three who lived to adulthood included Ira Hobart Evans, who won the Medal of Honor and became Speaker of the Texas House, and Edward, severely wounded at Cold Harbor in 1864."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Physician","organization":"Self / private practice","location":"Piermont, New Hampshire","end_year":1852}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"ira-evans-1802"},"TD0124":{"id":"TD0124","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":true,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"display_name":"Emeline Hobart Evans","first_name":"Emeline","last_name":"Evans","maiden_name":"Hobart","married_names":["Evans"],"gender":"female"},"birth":{"year":1811,"city":"Berlin","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1894,"city":"Piermont","county":"Grafton","state":"New Hampshire","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM176","plot_notes":"Berlin Corner Cemetery, Berlin Corners VT — alongside Dr. Ira."},"gender":"female","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":8,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{"father_id":"X02368","mother_id":"TD0120"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02383","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_husband","end_year":1852,"children_ids":["TD0158","TD0159","TD0160","TD0161","TD0162","TD0163","TD0164"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave — Emeline Hobart Evans","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/122836964/emeline-evans"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Mother of Civil War Medal of Honor recipient","body":"Emeline Hobart Evans was mother of Ira Hobart Evans — Civil War Medal of Honor recipient and later Speaker of the Texas House — and of three other surviving children. Of her seven total children, only three reached middle age: Mary Emeline who married Captain Thomas Blossom Yale, Edward P. (1842-1913 Civil War 10th Vermont Infantry severely wounded Cold Harbor), and Ira Hobart Evans (1844-1922). The two Civil War sons gave the family a doubled Vermont-regiment combat record from the same Berlin Vermont household."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Lost four of seven children before adulthood","body":"Emeline and Dr. Ira Evans's seven children included four childhood deaths: Mary E. (1834-1837, age 3); Ira (1836-1838, age 2 — the first attempt at the Ira name that her later son would carry); J. Annette (1840-1842, age 2); and William Dwight (1849-1861, age 12). All four were buried at Berlin Corner Cemetery in Vermont alongside their parents — a sequential-grief family burial cluster."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Widowed 1852, moved family to Barre Vermont","body":"After her husband Dr. Ira Evans died in 1852 at age forty-nine in Piermont New Hampshire, Emeline moved the family to Barre Vermont so her surviving sons could complete their education at Barre Academy — the pivot positioned both Edward and Ira Hobart Evans for their Civil War service paths. Emeline lived another forty-two years as widow, dying in 1894 around age eighty-three. She was born in 1811 in Berlin Vermont."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"emeline-hobart-evans-td0124"},"TD0158":{"id":"TD0158","former_i